
[1]premium

   PRE'MIUM, n. [L.] Properly, a reward or recompense; a prize to be won
   by competition; the reward or prize to be adjudged to the best
   performance or production.

   1. The recompense or prize offered for a specific discovery or for
   success in an enterprise; as for the discovery of the longitude, or of
   a northwest passage to the Pacific Ocean.

   2. A bounty; something offered or given for the loan of money, usually
   a sum beyond the interest.

   3. The recompense to underwriters for insurance, or for undertaking to
   indemnify for losses of any kind.

   4. It is sometimes synonymous with interest, but generally in obtaining
   loans, it is a sum per cent. distinct from the interest.

   The bank lends money to government at a premium of 2 per cent.

   5. A bounty.

   The law that obliges parishes to support the poor, offers a premium for
   the encouragement of idleness.
